Your vines shall mock scirocco blasts, Your crop the withering blight survive,

And when the dangerous autumn casts The apple, still your younglings thrive.

Yon heifer, mark, beneath some oak Of Algidus, oron the tracks

Of Alban meadows waits the stroke, To stain with gore the Pontifl's axe.

Not such for thee. Thy gods to sue, No crowd of yearlings slaughterest thou: Thou giv’st those modest gods their due With rosemary and myrtle bough.

Though gistless hands the altar touch, Our household gods gaze with content On cake and salt, and ask not such As costliest offerings present.-
